nothing wrong with streamlining, especially since in this case the complexity has gone up. it used to be that the competitive pvp format was 2v2/3v3s, but you could only queue for them with premade teams which meant you had to have friends in your skill range or engage in a lot of socialization with randoms to build teams. the new mode allows you to queue up solo then rotates through 6 matches with the same 8 people, so you can just do gaming without having to go proving yourself to anyone or getting in voice calls with strangers. they've also moved back to the philosophy of PvP gear being completely divorced from PvE gear so you don't end up in weird scenarios where you're forced to do raid at the highest level to PvP at all
i can't say that there's any less to do than raiding an pvp than there ever was, there's only so much content that can be interesting in the endgame. the infinite difficulty dungeon speedruns were and still are fun, but they haven't really been changed at all this expansion

i suppose we'll see before long
usually that's more of an upside fortunately. another problem with the old system was that if someone fucks up they can just kind of die instantly, so you could end up with queuing, load screens, and match prep time that lasted significantly longer than the match itself and that's not even accounting for the time spent finding a partner who might ditch you after 1 or 2 bad matches. it also ended up making the grindier matches feel like they took an absolute eternity in comparison even if they were only like 5 minutes long
with the new system you're commiting much more time when you queue up, but once you're in you get to play for 15-30 minutes more or less straight. it also makes learning far far easier since you're playing multiple back to back matches with/against the same few classes and skill levels
it's certainly not without some weird quirks, but i think it's an infinitely better system. fortunately it's an additional system with its own rating anyway rather than replacing the old one, so you can still just queue up for 2s or 3s with your buddies if you prefer that

>>16689260
you're probably thinking of pitch. tone is more about the texture and quality of the sound. it can be a bit nebulous especially since there are a lot of "correct" tone colors depending on the context and pinning down exactly what you do or don't like is difficult, but my sound currently is definitely a bit weak and hallow
it might be as simple as turning some nobs on the amp or just an unavoidable symptom of plugging headphones into it, but it might also have to do with stuff like how i'm plucking or my finger placement on the frets
on the bright side this is part of what draws me to bass instruments in the first place. higher pitched instruments have a much larger margin for error on tone quality, but they also have less options and it's infinitely more difficult to really dial in the fine details. it's really imperative that bass instruments have a perfect tone for it not to be pretty jarring, but that's not an unreasonable thing to ask of a tuba like it is for a flute

posts.com:
Some thoughts:

You may have been wondering when we were going to begin to focus on Jesus’ birth, after all, Christmas is coming! Often in the swirl of the season we can focus too narrowly on a single day or a single event. We have sought to remind us over the past couple of weeks that God’s purpose and plan for the birth of the Redeemer is in the context of bringing restoration to everything God has created. We begin observing the Christian Year at the very end of time, the Second Coming, the final advent of Jesus, and then work backwards to his birth and then forward to his Passion, Ascension, and advent of the Holy Spirit. You see, the Nativity has a much grander scope than simply the birth of baby Jesus. It is so much more significant than a Jesus’ birthday party!

This passage from Malachi is both a warning and a joyous promise to us. There is no doubt these words will come to pass and there will be judgment for all. Though his words were strong and clear, there is no evidence that the majority of those who heard Malachi’s message changed their crooked ways. Nevertheless, those who repented were known to God and were spared a severe judgment.

All people who honor the Lord will experience an abiding joy even in awful times. For them, there is no fear in judgment. The image of “leaping calves being led out to pasture” is another vivid image to a farm boy like me! How well I remember when in late March or early April, we opened the barn doors for the first time and let the calves, which had been penned up during the cold winter months, out into the fresh spring air. They ran and jumped around like little lambs or goats, almost out of control! Their little legs were wobbly with joy! We loved to watch the joy of those first minutes of newly discovered freedom. Malachi writes of this kind of joy along with the reminder to “remember history” and what God has done.
